Introduction

I am Christian Gruenewald, I successfully completed the Google Data Analytics Professional Certificate on Coursera over the past six months. This document provides an overview of my approach to the associated case study. My primary tools of choice for this analysis were BigQuery and Tableau. I will assume the role of a junior data analyst at a fictional bike-sharing company called Cyclistic throughout this case study. I will address key business questions through practical tasks and analysis employing the ask, Prepare, Process, Analyze, Share, and Act methodology.

Cyclistic

A bike-share program that features more than 5,800 bicycles and 600 docking stations. Cyclistic sets itself apart by also offering reclining bikes, hand tricycles, and cargo bikes, making bike-share more inclusive to people with disabilities and riders who can’t use a standard two-wheeled bike. Most riders opt for traditional bikes; about 8% of riders use the assistive options. Cyclistic users are more likely to ride for leisure, but about 30% use them to commute to work each day.

Until now, Cyclistic’s marketing strategy relied on building general awareness and appealing to broad consumer segments. One approach that helped make these things possible was the flexibility of its pricing plans: single-ride passes, full-day passes, and annual memberships. Customers who purchase single-ride or full-day passes are referred to as casual riders. Customers who purchase annual memberships are Cyclistic members.

Cyclistic’s finance analysts have concluded that annual members are much more profitable than casual riders. Although the pricing flexibility helps Cyclistic attract more customers, the director of marketing, Lily Moreno, believes that maximizing the number of annual members will be key to future growth. Rather than creating a marketing campaign that targets all-new customers, Moreno believes there is a particularly good chance to convert casual riders into members. She notes that casual riders are already aware of the Cyclistic program and have chosen Cyclistic for their mobility needs.

Moreno has set a clear goal: Design marketing strategies aimed at converting casual riders into annual members. To do that, however, the marketing analyst team needs to better understand how annual members and casual riders differ, why casual riders would buy a membership, and how digital media could affect their marketing tactics. Moreno and her team are interested in analyzing the Cyclistic historical bike trip data to identify trends.

Scenario

As a Junior Data Analyst within the Marketing Analyst team at Cyclistic, a prominent bike-share company based in Chicago, I am entrusted with the pivotal task of contributing to the company’s strategic success. Under the visionary leadership of Director of Marketing, Lily Moreno, our collective focus centers on the maximization of annual memberships as a cornerstone for sustained growth.

To realize this objective, our team is diligently engaged in unraveling the nuanced distinctions in the utilization patterns between casual riders and annual members on the Cyclistic bike-sharing platform. The culmination of these insights will lay the groundwork for the meticulous design of a novel marketing strategy, one that is tailored to effectively convert casual riders into coveted annual members.

However, recognizing the significance of securing executive approval, our immediate precursor involves the compelling presentation of data insights and the creation of professional data visualizations. This prerequisite step ensures that our proposed marketing strategy is underpinned by substantiated evidence and resonates seamlessly with Cyclist’s overarching business objectives. The commitment to precision, professionalism, and data-driven decision-making underscores our dedication to delivering impactful results for Cyclistic’s future success.

Methodolgy

Ask

Business Task: Designing Marketing Strategies for Annual Membership Conversion

Objective: Create three effective marketing strategies targeting casual riders with the goal of converting them into annual members.

Task Description:

As a junior data analyst at Cyclistic, our marketing analyst team was tasked with understanding the usage patterns of casual riders and annual members to design compelling marketing strategies for converting casual riders into annual members. The overarching goal was to maximize the number of annual memberships, aligning with the company’s future success vision.

Objectives:

A. Obtain, Clean, and Aggregate Historical Trip Data:
  1. Identify and acquire historical Cyclistic trip data from relevant sources.
  2. Perform data cleaning and aggregation to ensure data quality and consistency.
  3. Document all cleaning and manipulation processes for transparency.
B. Analysis of Historical Trip Data:
  1. Conduct a thorough analysis of historical trip data to uncover insights into how casual riders and annual members utilize Cyclistic bikes differently.
  2. Utilize statistical methods and data visualization techniques to identify patterns, trends, and significant differences.
  3. Generate compelling visualizations to present key findings.
C. Design Three Effective Marketing Strategies:
  1. Based on the analysis, propose three distinct marketing strategies targeted towards converting casual riders into annual members.
  2. Each strategy should be supported by data-driven insights from the analysis.
  3. Provide detailed documentation of the rationale behind each strategy.

Deliverables

  • A concise and clear articulation of the business task, emphasizing the goal of maximizing annual memberships through targeted marketing strategies.

Data Sources:

  • Documentation of all data sources used, specifying the origin and nature of the historical Cyclistic trip data.

  • Detailed documentation of the steps taken to clean and manipulate the data, ensuring reproducibility and transparency in the analysis.

Summary of Analysis:

  • A comprehensive summary of the analysis, highlighting key insights derived from the historical trip data.

By successfully completing these tasks and delivering the outlined documentation and insights, I aimed to provide Cyclistic executives with compelling data-driven recommendations for the development of an effective marketing strategies to convert casual riders into annual members.

Prepare

Data Source

The data used for this case study comes from Cyclistic’s historical trip data and can be found here. Note: The data sets have a different name because Cyclistic is a fictional company. For the purposes of this case study, the data sets are appropriate and will enable you to answer the business questions. The data has been made available by Motivate International Inc. under this license.

Currently only 11 months of 2023 are available to use. However, I want to use one year of the most current data possible, so we will use the last month of 2022 to fill in the gaps. This means that the data will go from December 1, 2022 - November 31, 2023.

Data Organization

The 12 files used for analysis used the naming convention of YYYYMM-divvy-tripdata. This was a little hard to read so I changed all the file names to month-YYYY-tripdata. Each file contains one month of trip data including: ride_id, rideable_type, started_at, ended_at, start_station_name, end_station_name, start_station_id, end_station_id, start_lat, start_lng, end_lat, end_lng, member_casual.

Process

For the initial phase of data processing, I opted for the utilization of BigQuery, driven by its capacity to manage extensive file sizes efficiently. The imperative task involves consolidating all pertinent data into a singular data set, culminating in approximately 5.6 million rows. The choice of BigQuery stems from its robust capabilities in managing large-scale data sets, as executing comparable functions in alternative types of software would be highly impractical due to the substantial time required for execution.

Data Aggregation

The process of data aggregation commenced with the ingestion of cycling data spanning twelve months into a BigQuery environment. Subsequently, a union operation was executed to amalgamate all individual data sets, resulting in the creation of a consolidated master table denominated as ‘2023-combined-tripdata,’ encompassing a total of 5,677,610 rows. This unified data set now serves as the foundation for comprehensive examination and analysis, facilitating a holistic understanding of the aggregated cycling data.

create table if not exists `12_2022.2023-combined-tripdata` AS (
  select * from `12_2022.Dec-2022-tripdata`
  union all
  select * from `12_2022.Jan-2023-tripdata`
  union all
  select * from `12_2022.Feb-2023-tripdata`
  union all
  select * from `12_2022.Mar-2023-tripdata`
  union all
  select * from `12_2022.Apr-2023-tripdata`
  union all
  select * from `12_2022.May-2023-tripdata`
  union all
  select * from `12_2022.Jun-2023-tripdata`
  union all
  select * from `12_2022.Jul-2023-tripdata`
  union all
  select * from `12_2022.Aug-2023-tripdata`
  union all
  select * from `12_2022.Sep-2023-tripdata`
  union all
  select * from `12_2022.Oct-2023-tripdata`
  union all
  select * from `12_2022.Nov-2023-tripdata`
);

Data Observations

  1. The initial step involved a meticulous examination of the data’s schema, with particular emphasis on recognizing ride_id as the primary key, essential for subsequent data operations and analyses.


  2. Subsequently, attention was directed towards the identification of null values within the data set. Executing a query to quantify null occurrences in each column generates a new table, revealing a substantial volume of null values necessitating comprehensive cleaning.

  3. Verification of data integrity was performed by scrutinizing ride_id for duplicates. A query was constructed to ascertain the count of distinct values in the ride_id column, and upon deduction from the total count, zero duplicate rows are observed, ensuring the uniqueness of the primary key.

  4. Analysis extends to the categorical variable ridable_type, featuring three distinct types: electric_bike, classic_bike, and docked_bike, warranting a nuanced examination of their distribution.


  5. Attention was then directed towards the temporal attributes start_at and end_at, formatted as YYYY-MM-DD hh:mm:ss. These columns serve as the basis for deriving a new column named ride_duration, quantifying the duration of each ride in seconds. Four supplementary columns, namely trip_duration, time_start, date_start, and week_day, were introduced to enhance analysis capabilities using the following SQL queries: 

CREATE TABLE `analog-premise-409620.12_2022.2023-combined-tripdataV2`
AS 
SELECT 
*, 
TIMESTAMP_DIFF(ended_at, started_at, SECOND) AS trip_duration

FROM `analog-premise-409620.12_2022.2023-combined-tripdata` 
CREATE TABLE `analog-premise-409620.12_2022.2023-combined-tripdataV3`
AS 
SELECT 
*, 
DATE(started_at) AS date_start,
TIME(started_at) AS time_start

FROM `analog-premise-409620.12_2022.2023-combined-tripdataV2` 
CREATE TABLE `analog-premise-409620.12_2022.2023-combined-tripdataV4`
AS 
SELECT 
*, 
FORMAT_DATE('%A', DATE(started_at)) AS week_day

FROM `analog-premise-409620.12_2022.2023-combined-tripdataV3`

  1. The analysis proceeds to scrutinize start_station_name, start_station_id, end_station_name, and end_station_id. Recognizing the insignificance of start_station_id and end_station_id in the analytical context, both were expunged from the data set to streamline subsequent analyses.

  2. Concluding the examination, the data set encapsulates the variable member_casual, a pivotal attribute delineating whether a ride was executed by a registered member or a casual rider. This binary classification serves as a crucial deliminator in discerning distinct usage patterns and behaviors within the Cyclistic bike-sharing platform. Further exploration and segmentation based on this categorical variable will contribute valuable insights for the subsequent phases of our analytical endeavors.

Data Cleaning

  1. Data cleaning started by checking for duplicate data. I used this SQL query to complete this.
SELECT count(ride_id)- count(DISTINCT(ride_id)) as duplicates
 FROM `analog-premise-409620.12_2022.2023-combined-tripdata`
  1. Second the columns start_station_id and end_station_id were removed with the following queries.

Analyze

Initiating the analytical phase of this case study required a strategic reevaluation of the core question: How do annual members and casual riders exhibit differential utilization patterns within the Cyclistic bike-sharing platform? The analytical framework encompasses several key dimensions:

  1. Bike Utilization Patterns:
  • An exploration of the bike types preferred by annual members and casual riders, providing insights into the distinctive choices made by each user category.
  1. Temporal Analysis:
  • Examination of the total number of rides on an hourly, daily, and monthly basis, shedding light on temporal trends in user engagement for both annual members and casual riders.
  1. Trip Duration Analysis:
  • Analysis of the average trip duration, scrutinized hourly, daily, and monthly, unraveling patterns in ride durations and potential variations between annual members and casual riders.
  1. Station Popularity Analysis:
  • Investigation into the most frequented stations by casual riders compared to members, discerning station preferences and potential disparities in user behavior.

All visualizations presented herein were meticulously crafted utilizing Tableau, ensuring a professional and data-driven representation of the intricate patterns and trends identified throughout the analysis. The comprehensive exploration of these facets aimed to provide actionable insights for the subsequent formulation of targeted marketing strategies to enhance annual membership conversion.

Bike Utilization Patterns:


A detailed examination of the data revealed that Cyclistic members contribute to 67% of the overall utilization of standard bikes and 62% of the total usage of electric bikes. Notably, the entirety of docked bike usage was attributed to non-members. This statistical breakdown underscores the pronounced influence of Cyclistic members on specific bike types, delineating a nuanced understanding of bike preference and utilization patterns among different user categories.

Temporal Analysis:


Monthly Ride Trends:

This graphical representation highlights a consistent pattern where Cyclistic members consistently contribute approximately 100,000 more rides per month compared to casual riders. Additionally, discernible peaks in ride frequency were observed during the months spanning from May to September, indicating a pronounced seasonal trend.



Weekday Analysis:

A thorough examination of the total number of rides categorized by the day of the week unveils distinct behavioral trends. Weekends emerge as the period with the highest casual rider engagement, while Cyclistic members exhibit a more uniform distribution of rides throughout the week, showcasing their consistent usage pattern.



Hourly Utilization Patterns:

Delving into the temporal dimension, a detailed analysis of total rides by the time of day elucidates intriguing insights. Cyclistic members displayed peak usage at 8 am and 5 pm, indicative of potential commuting patterns. In contrast, non-members exhibit their peak usage at 5 pm, suggesting a different temporal utilization trend associated with distinct user behaviors.

Trip Duration Analysis:

Upon scrutinizing the average trip duration for distinct customer types, a conspicuous pattern emerges, highlighting that non-members consistently embark on significantly longer rides compared to Cyclistic members. Notably, this distinction becomes particularly pronounced during the favorable weather months, where non-members exhibit a ride duration twice as long as that of members. This temporal and behavioral disparity in trip durations underscores noteworthy distinctions in user preferences and engagement patterns between the two customer segments.

Station Popularity Analysis:

The analysis of starting and ending locations for both customer types revealed a notable similarity, with little discernible difference between the two. Nevertheless, an observation was made that non-members exhibit a more localized pattern, particularly along the coastal areas. This spatial insight suggests a potential geographic concentration in the riding behavior of non-members, contributing to a nuanced understanding of user preferences and spatial utilization patterns across customer segments.

Summary

The comprehensive analysis of Cyclistic bike-sharing data delineates substantive differentiation between members and casual riders, offering nuanced insights into user behavior and preferences. Key findings include:

  1. Bike Utilization Patterns:
  • Cyclistic members prominently influence the usage of standard and electric bikes, contributing to 67% and 62% of the respective categories. Conversely, all docked bike usage was attributed to non-members, highlighting distinct preferences in bike types.
  1. Temporal Trends:
  • Members consistently exhibit a higher ride frequency, contributing approximately 100,000 more rides per month. The peak riding season spans from May to September, aligning with favorable weather conditions. Weekends witness heightened engagement from casual riders, while members maintain a consistent pattern throughout the week.
  1. Hourly Utilization Patterns:
  • Analysis of ride distribution by time of day reveals distinctive temporal preferences. Members peak at 8 am and 5 pm, indicative of potential commuting behavior. Non-members, in contrast, exhibit peak usage at 5 pm, suggesting divergent temporal utilization patterns.
  1. Average Trip Duration:
  • A significant divergence emerges in average trip duration, with non-members consistently riding substantially longer than members. During favorable weather months, non-members’ ride duration is twice that of members, underscoring a pronounced temporal and behavioral disparity.
  1. Spatial Utilization Patterns:
  • Examination of starting and ending locations indicates a similarity between members and casual riders. However, a notable observation is that non-members exhibit a more localized pattern, particularly along coastal areas, suggesting distinct geographic concentration in their riding behavior.

This multifaceted analysis provides a comprehensive foundation for informing targeted marketing strategies aimed at converting casual riders into annual members. The identified differences offer strategic insights for Cyclistic in tailoring initiatives that resonate with the specific preferences and behaviors of each customer segment.

Act

Having successfully addressed the question surrounding the disparate utilization patterns between annual members and casual riders within the Cyclistic bike-sharing platform, I can leverage my analytical findings to formulate three discerning marketing strategies.

Strategy 1: Seasonal Targeting

  • Utilizing the observed peak riding season from May to September, an optimal marketing strategy entails targeted initiatives during these months. Focused efforts during this period align with heightened engagement and favorable weather conditions, maximizing the impact on casual riders.

Strategy 2: Weekend-Centric Campaigns

  • The second strategic imperative recommends structuring marketing campaigns to coincide with weekends, notably when casual rider engagement reaches its zenith. Aligning promotional activities with these temporal peaks ensures targeted outreach during periods of heightened user participation, enhancing the effectiveness of marketing endeavors.

Strategy 3: Station-Centric Campaigns

  • The third strategy underscores the importance of directing marketing efforts to the top five most frequented stations by casual riders. This station-centric approach acknowledges the significance of geographic concentration in non-member riding behavior, optimizing promotional impact by tailoring campaigns to locations of pronounced user activity.

By meticulously tailoring marketing initiatives to these three strategies, Cyclistic can adeptly channel resources and promotional efforts, enhancing the likelihood of converting casual riders into annual members. These strategic directives are grounded in empirical data insights, fostering a data-driven and targeted approach to marketing optimization.
